{{main|Provinces and territories of Canada}}

'''[[Canada]]''' is divided into ten [[Provinces and territories of Canada|provinces]] and three [[Provinces and territories of Canada|territories]].

Each province has a different system of [[local government]] which may include upper-tier or rural jurisdictions such as [[county|counties]], [[municipal district]]s, [[regional municipality|regional municipalities]], [[regional district]]s or [[regional county municipality|regional county municipalities]]. These divisions are then divided into lower-tier or urban jurisdictions such as [[List of cities in Canada|cities]], [[town]]s, [[village]]s, [[township (Canada)|township]]s, and [[parish (administrative division)|parish]]es. Cities in [[Quebec]] are further subdivided into [[Boroughs of Canada|arrondissements]] (similar to [[Boroughs of Montreal|boroughs]]), while outside of Quebec cities are divided into [[Ward (electoral subdivision)|wards]].

{{Canada provinces map|align=right |AB =Census divisions of Alberta|BC =Regional districts of British Columbia|SK = Census divisions of Saskatchewan|MB = Census divisions of Manitoba|ON = Census divisions of Ontario|QC = List of Quebec regions|NB = Counties of New Brunswick|PE = Counties of Prince Edward Island|NS = Counties of Nova Scotia|NL = Census divisions of Newfoundland and Labrador|NT=Regions of the Northwest Territories|NU=Regions of Nunavut|Map=Canada-census layout.png|caption=Census Divisions by province and territory}}

[[Statistics Canada]] aggregates statistical [[census]] data into [[Census divisions of Canada|census divisions]], which follow boundaries of one or more large local government units. Municipalities (and in some cases, communities within municipalities) within census divisions may be considered [[census subdivisions]].

